Store block information

Satya Golla and Steve Simon

Created 2022-03-12

This program will read in census shapefiles for census blocks, convert them into the simple features (sf) format, and store the results for later use.

General information

The starting point for downloading most Census shapefiles is here. The ftp site is a bit more difficult to navigate, but leads you directly to the files that you want.

It helps to know the FIPS (Federal Information Processing System) codes for Kansas (20) and Missouri (29).

US census blocks

A census block is the smallest geographical unit used by the United States Census Bureau for tabulation of 100-percent data. There are files for census blocks for [Kansas][c]

There is a single file of counties for all of the United States. Use the st_read function from the sf package to read in the data. You may need to convert the coordinate reference system. That uses the st_crs function, also of the sf package. Counties are uniquely identified by a two digit state FIPS code and a three digit county FIPS code. These are combined into a five digit code, GEOID.

The important counties for this program are

Johnson County, KS (20091) Leavenworth County, KS (20103) Wyandotte County, KS (20209) Cass County, MO (29037) Clay County, MO (29047) Jackson County, MO (29095) Platte County, KS (29165)

Read county shapefiles

Store as an RData file

Placing the file in an RData format will speed up future use of this file.

s20091                                 %>%
  bind_rows(s20103)                    %>%
  bind_rows(s20209)                    %>%
  bind_rows(s29037)                    %>%
  bind_rows(s29047)                    %>%
  bind_rows(s29095)                    %>%
  bind_rows(s29165)                    %>%
  mutate(label=GEOID20)                %>%
  rename(statefp=STATEFP20)            %>%
  rename(countyfp=COUNTYFP20)          %>%
  rename(tract=TRACTCE20)              %>%
  rename(block=BLOCKCE20)               -> bl
bl                                     %>%
  mutate(
    block_area=
      as.numeric(st_area(bl)))          -> bl
save(bl, file="../data/bl0.RData")

An alternate set of shape files appear under the names

  • TIGER2020/TABBLOCK/tl_2020_xx_tabblock10.zip
  • TIGER2020/TABBLOCK20/tl_2020_xx_tabblock20.zip

ks_list <- c(
  "091",
  "103",
  "209")
file_name <- "bl2/tl_2020_20_tabblock10.shp"
path_name                              %>%
  paste(file_name, sep="/")            %>%
  st_read(stringsAsFactors=FALSE)      %>%
  filter(COUNTYFP10 %in% ks_list)       -> bl2ks
